Lambda Expressions in Java

A lambda expression is a short way to write a function (method) without creating a class.

👉 Introduced in Java 8 to make code cleaner and more concise.

Basic Syntax
(parameters) -> expression

или

(parameters) -> {
    // multiple lines
}
Simple Example
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

👉 вместо:

Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
};
Functional Interface (Important)

👉 Lambda works only with functional interfaces

A functional interface:

has one abstract method

Examples:

Runnable
Comparator
Callable
Example with Comparator
list.sort((a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
Lambda Variations
No parameters
() -> System.out.println("Hello")
One parameter
x -> x * 2
Multiple parameters
(a, b) -> a + b
Multiple statements
(a, b) -> {
    int sum = a + b;
    return sum;
}
Why use Lambda?
less code
more readable
functional programming style
widely used with collections and streams
Common Use Cases
sorting (Comparator)
filtering
iteration (forEach)
Example with forEach
list.forEach(item -> System.out.println(item));
Lambda vs Anonymous Class
Lambda	Anonymous Class
shorter	longer
cleaner	more verbose
only functional interface	can implement any class/interface
Summary
lambda = short function syntax
works with functional interfaces
reduces boilerplate code
widely used in modern Java
